    "number": 35308,
    "state": "open",
    "state_reason": "reopened",
    "title": "BIP32: CExtKey::SetSeed missing validation of seed bit-length",
    "body": "### Current behaviour\n\n[CExtKey::SetSeed](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/master/src/key.cpp#L368) does not check the seed bit-length constraints [defined in BIP32](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0032.mediawiki?plain=1#L148)\n\n> Generate a seed byte sequence S of a chosen length (between 128 and 512 bits; 256 bits is advised) from a (P)RNG.\n\nI don't see a reason for not adhering to the spec in this case. Weak seeds used for master key generation can & [have been exploited](https://is.muni.cz/th/pnmt2/).\n\nFound using the [bitcoinfuzz](https://github.com/bitcoinfuzz/bitcoinfuzz) tool.\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\n[CExtKey::SetSeed](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/master/src/key.cpp#L368) should provide bit-length (or byte-length) checks for the parameter `seed`\ne.g.,\n```\nvoid CExtKey::SetSeed(std::span<const std::byte> seed)\n{\n    if (seed.size() < 16) return; // or throw\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nAdded a testcase in [key_tests.cpp](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/ed1795aa17205db6ac15fa7ea1645357740b26ac/src/test/key_tests.cpp) and ran the tests:\n\n\n```\nBOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE(extkey_setseed_empty)\n{\n    CExtKey key;\n    \n    // Test with 0 bytes\n    std::vector<std::byte> empty{};\n    key.SetSeed(empty);\n\n    // Test with 1 byte\n    std::vector<std::byte> one{std::byte{0x01}};\n    key.SetSeed(one);\n    \n}\n```\n```\nRunning 8 test cases...\n\n*** No errors detected\n```\n\n### How did you obtain Bitcoin Core\n\nCompiled from source\n\n### What version of Bitcoin Core are you using?\n\nmaster@ed1795a\n\n### Operating system and version\n\nUbuntu 24.04.3 LTS\n",
